141. 4. fissum rororis: probably a fissure or cut separating the dif- ferent lobes of the liver, called limes in Seneca OEd. 365. The fissure denoted good or evil fortune according to the circumstances; there was a fissum vitale, a fissum familiare, and other similar sorts. See De Div. 11, 6, 12. 133 Brisson. De Form. I, 31; Miiller Etrusk. II, 182.

141. 4. sortis, such as were used in the temple of Fortuna at Prae- neste for divination; they were counters, which when mixed like a pack of cards were thrown into a vase, and one or more were drawn out. Hense the expressions sortes aequare, sortem ducere or trahere. Comp. De Div. I, 18, 34; II, 33, 703 41, 963 Suet. Tiber. 14. The sortes were not all of the same kind, and those expressions do not have the same mean· ing with all.
